    <subsection>
    <title>Activities</title>
    <observation>
      <p>We have seen previously that we can reduce rational functions by factoring, for example
        <me>\frac{x^2+5x+4}{x^4+3x^2+2x}=\frac{(x+1)(x+4)}{x(x+2)(x+1)}=\frac{x+4}{x(x+2)}.</me>
        In this section, we wille explore what can we do to simplify rational functions if we are not able to 
        reduce by easily factoring?
    </p>
  </observation>
    <definition xml:id="proper-rational-function">
      <statement>
        <p> Recall that a fraction is called <term>proper</term> if its numerator is smaller than its denominator, and <term>improper</term> 
          if the numerator is larger than the denominator (so <m>\frac{3}{5}</m> is a proper fraction, but <m>\frac{32}{7}</m> is an 
          improper fraction).  Similarly, we define a <term>proper rational function</term> to be a rational function where 
          the degree of the numerator is less than the degree of the denominator.  </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity xml:id="identify-improper-rational-functions">
      <statement>
        Label each of the following rational functions as either <term>proper</term> or <term>improper</term>.
        <ol marker="A.">
          <li><m> \frac{x^3+x}{x^2+4}</m></li>
          <li><m> \frac{3}{x^2+3x+4}</m></li>
          <li><m> \frac{7+x^3}{x^2+x+1}</m></li>
          <li><m> \frac{x^4+x+1}{x^4+4x^2}</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </activity>

    <observation>
      <p>When dealing with an improper fraction such as <m>\frac{32}{7}</m>, it is sometimes useful to rewrite this
        as an integer plus an improper fraction <m>\frac{32}{7}=4+\frac{4}{7}</m>.  Similarly, it will sometimes be
        useful to rewrite an improper rational function as the sum of a polynomial and a proper rational function, such 
        as <m>\frac{x^3+x}{x^2+4}=x-\frac{3x}{x^2+4}</m>.
      </p>
    </observation>

    <activity xml:id="Long-division-integer">
    <introduction>
      Consider the improper fraction <m>\frac{357}{11}</m>.
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>Use long division to write <m>\frac{357}{11}</m> as an integer plus a proper fraction.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p>Now we will carefully redo this process in a way that we can generalize to rational functions.  
      Note that we can rewrite <m>357</m> as <m>357=3*10^2+5*10+7</m>, and <m>11</m> as <m>11=1*10+1</m>. 
      By comparing the leading terms in these expansions, we see that to knock off the leading term of <m>357</m>, we need to
      multiply <m>11</m> by <m>3*10^1</m>.
    </p>
    <p>Using the fact that <m>357=11*30+27</m>, rewrite <m>\frac{357}{11}</m> as <m>\frac{357}{11}=30+\frac{?}{11}</m>.
    </p>
      </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p>Note now that if we can rewrite <m>\frac{27}{11}</m> as an integer plus a proper fraction, we will be done, 
      since <m>\frac{357}{11}=30+\frac{27}{11}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Rewrite <m>27=?+\frac{?}{11}</m> as an integer plus a proper fraction.
    </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p>Combine your work in the previous two parts to rewrite <m>\frac{357}{11}</m> as an integer plus a proper fraction.  
      How does this compare to what you obtained in part (a)?
    </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  </activity>

<activity xml:id="long-division-activity-1">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Now let's consider the rational function <m>\frac{3x^2+5x+7}{x+1}</m>.  We want to rewrite this as a polynomial
      plus a proper rational function.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p>Looking at the leading terms, what do we need to multiply <m>x+1</m> by so that it would have the same leading term
      as <m>3x^2+5x+7</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p>Rewrite <m>3x^2+5x+7=3x(x+1)+?</m>, and use this to rewrite <m>\frac{3x^2+5x+7}{x+1}=3x+\frac{?}{x+1}</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p>
      Now focusing on <m>\frac{2x+7}{x+1}</m>, what do we need to multiply <m>x+1</m> by so that it would have the same leading term
      as <m>2x+7</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
  <p> Rewrite <m>\frac{2x+7}{x+1}=2x+\frac{?}{x+1}</m>.</p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p>Combine this with the previous parts to rewrite <m>\frac{3x^2+5x+7}{x+1}=3x+?+\frac{?}{x+1}</m>.</p>
    </statement>
  </task>
</activity>

    <activity xml:id="Long-Division-Basic">
      
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>346 can be written as <m> 3*10^2+4*10+7</m>. This is equivalent to the polynomial <m>f(x)=3x^2+4x+7</m> for <m>f(10)</m>. <m>17</m> can be written as <m>10+7</m>, which is equivalent to the polynomial <m>f(x)=x+7</m> for <m>f(10)</m>. Use long division to find the quotient and remainder when 346 is divided by 17. 
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> quotient 20, remainder 3</li>
            <li> quotient 6, remainder 3</li>
            <li> quotient 6, remainder 20</li>
            <li> quotient 20, remainder 6</li>
            </ol></p>
          </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
            <p>What is the divisor?
              <ol marker= "A.">
                <li> <m>3</m></li>
                <li> <m>17</m></li>
                <li> <m>20</m></li>
                <li> <m>6</m></li>
                </ol>  
          </p> 
        </statement>
        </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
          <p>Now write the answer as a mixed number.
            <ol marker= "A.">
              <li> <m>20 + \frac{3}{17}</m></li>
              <li> <m>6 + \frac{20}{17}</m></li>
              <li> <m>20 + \frac{6}{17}</m></li>
              <li> <m>6 + \frac{3}{17}</m></li>
              </ol>  
        </p> </statement>
      </task>
       
        <task> 
          <statement>
          <p>Is the fraction portion of the mixed number a proper or improper fraction?
           </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      
      <task> 
        <statement>
          <p>How can you check your answer?  </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="Simplify-Rational-By-Factoring">
      
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>Now let's try simplifying a different rational function, in a generalized format, where <m>x</m> is unknown.  
           <m>f(x)=\frac{3x^2+11x-4}{x+4}</m>
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> <m>x+4</m></li>
            <li> <m>3x-1</m></li>
            <li> <m>x-4</m></li>
            <li> <m>3x+1</m></li>
            </ol></p> 
          </statement>
        </task> 
        
       
     
    </activity>
  
   
    <activity xml:id="Long-Division-Intro-Steps">
        <introduction>
          <p>Now we will simplify using long division, given <m>f(x)=\frac{3x^2+11x-4}{x+4}</m>.</p> 
        </introduction>
       
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>What is the result when <m>3x^2</m> is divided by <m>x</m>? Place this number at the top left when doing long division.
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> <m>3</m></li>
            <li> <m>3x</m></li>
            <li> <m>3x^3</m></li>
            </ol>  
      </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>Next, multiply this result by <m>x+4</m> and write this below <m>3x^2+11x-4 </m>. Be sure to line up like terms in the same column. What is the result?
          <ol marker= "A.">
          <li> <m>3x^2+12x</m></li>
          <li> <m>-3x^2-12x</m></li>
          <li> <m>3x^3+12x</m></li>
          </ol>  </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>Now subtract the like terms by placing them in the corresponding columns.
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> <m>-3x^2-x-4</m></li>
            <li> <m>x+4</m></li>
            <li> <m>23x-4</m></li>
            <li> <m>-x-4</m></li>
            </ol>  </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p> Next, divide the first term in the previous result by <m>x</m>. Write the answer on the top beside the first answer. What is the expression at the top now?
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> <m>3x^2-1</m></li>
            <li> <m>-3x+1</m></li>
            <li> <m>3x-1</m></li>
            <li> <m>3x+1</m></li>
            </ol>  </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>Multiply this resulting term by <m>x+4</m> and write that answer in the proper columns of like terms. What is this result? 
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> <m>-x-4</m></li>
            <li> <m>x+4</m></li>
            </ol>  </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>Subtract the like terms. This is the remainder. What is the remainder? 
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> <m>2x+8</m></li>
            <li> <m>-x-4</m></li>
            <li> <m>0</m></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>What is the quotient? 
          <ol marker= "A.">
            <li> <m>3x^2+11x-4</m></li>
            <li> <m>3x-1</m></li>
            <li> <m>0</m></li>
            <li> <m>x+4</m></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>How can you check your answer? (Hint: Think of regular long division with positive integers.) </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task> 
          <statement>
            <p>How does your answer for the quotient and remainder compare to the simplifying by factoring method? </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
      </activity>

